y, marriage and motherhood – and the health problems connected to them – infertility, birth control and abortion, gynaecology, cancer, nervous disorders, and menopause. Mitchinson provides a sensitive understanding of the physician/patient relationship, the unease of many doctors about the bodies of their female patients, as well as overriding concerns about the relationship between female and male bodies. Throughout the book, Mitchinson takes care to examine the roles and agency of both patients and practitioners as diverse individuals.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aMedicinezCanadaxHistoryy20th century. 0aPhysician and patientzCanadaxHistoryy20th century. 0aWomen patientszCanadaxHistoryy20th century. 0aWomenxHealth and hygienezCanadaxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / Canada / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144266527940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442665279423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442665279.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK